# Reconcile Best Practices for Kubebuilder ({{.Version}})

Use these guidelines when implementing the `Reconcile` function of a Kubernetes controller.

## Idempotency

Every `Reconcile` call must be safe to run multiple times.
Do not assume the function is called only once per change.
Write state by applying desired state, not by diffing.

## Fetch and return early on not-found

```go
var obj myv1.MyKind
if err := r.Get(ctx, req.NamespacedName, &obj); err != nil {
    return ctrl.Result{}, client.IgnoreNotFound(err)
}
```

Always ignore `NotFound` errors from `Get` — the object may have been deleted
before the reconcile ran.

## Status conditions

Use `metav1.Condition` and `apimeta.SetStatusCondition` to record meaningful
status on your resource. Prefer standard condition types (`Ready`, `Degraded`,
`Progressing`) before inventing custom ones.

Always update `.Status` with a patch (not a full `Update`) to avoid conflicts:

```go
patch := client.MergeFrom(obj.DeepCopy())
// ... modify obj.Status ...
if err := r.Status().Patch(ctx, &obj, patch); err != nil {
    return ctrl.Result{}, err
}
```

## Finalizers

Add a finalizer in the reconcile loop when the resource needs cleanup:

```go
if obj.DeletionTimestamp.IsZero() {
    if !controllerutil.ContainsFinalizer(&obj, myFinalizer) {
        controllerutil.AddFinalizer(&obj, myFinalizer)
        return ctrl.Result{}, r.Update(ctx, &obj)
    }
} else {
    if controllerutil.ContainsFinalizer(&obj, myFinalizer) {
        if err := r.cleanup(ctx, &obj); err != nil {
            return ctrl.Result{}, err
        }
        controllerutil.RemoveFinalizer(&obj, myFinalizer)
        return ctrl.Result{}, r.Update(ctx, &obj)
    }
}
```

## Requeue and backoff

- Return `ctrl.Result{}` (no requeue) on success.
- Return `ctrl.Result{}, err` to requeue with exponential back-off.
- Return `ctrl.Result{RequeueAfter: d}` to poll at a fixed interval.
- Avoid `Requeue: true` (immediately requeues with no back-off).

## Avoid tight status-update loops

Do not call `r.Status().Update` or `r.Status().Patch` inside a tight loop.
Each call triggers a new watch event and can cause a reconcile storm.

## Watch ownership

Use `ctrl.SetupWithManager(mgr).Owns(&owned{})` to automatically requeue the
owner when an owned object changes. Use `Watches` with a custom handler for
cross-resource dependencies.

## Logging

Use structured logging with `log.FromContext(ctx)`.
Always add the object namespace and name:

```go
log := log.FromContext(ctx)
log.Info("Reconciling", "generation", obj.Generation)
```

